---

<BaseLayout
  title="Dog Daycare Software for UK Facilities | MyPetCare"
  description="Stop losing 15+ hours a week to spreadsheets and phone calls. MyPetCare handles bookings, capacity, vaccinations, and report cards for dog daycare facilities. From £79/month."
  image="/images/hero-pets.jpg"
>
  <!-- Breadcrumbs with Schema -->
  <div class="bg-gray-100 py-3">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <BreadcrumbsEnhanced items={breadcrumbs} site="petcare" />
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-gradient-to-br from-brand-navy to-gray-900 text-white py-16">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 opacity-10">
      <div class="absolute inset-0" style="background-image: url('/images/hero-daycare.jpg'); background-size: cover; background-position: center;"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="container-custom relative">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <span class="inline-block bg-brand-red/20 text-brand-red-light px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-sm mb-4">Built for UK Dog Daycare Operators</span>
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-6">Dog Daycare Software That Handles the Admin, So You Can Focus on the Dogs</h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-gray-300 mb-8">
          Online bookings, real-time capacity management, vaccination tracking, and photo report cards — all in one place. No more spreadsheets. No more missed calls.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4">
          <a href="/contact/" class="btn-primary text-lg px-8 py-4">Start Free Trial</a>
          <a href="/early-access/" class="btn-secondary text-lg px-8 py-4">Join Early Access</a>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mt-3">No credit card required · Set up in under 15 minutes</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Featured Answer for Featured Snippet -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <FeaturedAnswer question="What is dog daycare software?">
          Dog daycare software is an all-in-one management platform for dog daycare facilities that handles online bookings, real-time capacity management, vaccination tracking, owner portals, report cards with photos, automated reminders, and integrated billing. Purpose-built systems help UK facilities save 12–18 hours per week while reducing phone calls by up to 60%.
        </FeaturedAnswer>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Statistics Section with Dataset Schema -->
  <section class="section bg-gray-50">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <StatisticsSection
          title="UK Dog Daycare Industry Statistics 2025–2026"
          description="Key metrics on the growth and digitalisation of the UK pet care sector"
          stats={petCareStats}
          layout="grid"
          source="PFMA Pet Population Report 2024; Statista UK Pet Care Market 2025; CFSG Pet Industry Census 2024"
          datePublished="2026-01-01"
          site="petcare"
          pageUrl={Astro.url.href}
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Table of Contents -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-200">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-4">In This Guide</h2>
          <ul class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-2 text-gray-700">
            <li><a href="#problem" class="hover:text-brand-red">→ Why Daycare Admin Is So Hard</a></li>
            <li><a href="#what-is" class="hover:text-brand-red">→ What Daycare Software Does</a></li>
            <li><a href="#features" class="hover:text-brand-red">→ Key Features Explained</a></li>
            <li><a href="#comparison" class="hover:text-brand-red">→ Feature Comparison</a></li>
            <li><a href="#case-study" class="hover:text-brand-red">→ Case Study: Tails & Trails</a></li>
            <li><a href="#choosing" class="hover:text-brand-red">→ How to Choose</a></li>
            <li><a href="#early-access" class="hover:text-brand-red">→ Early Access Programme</a></li>
            <li><a href="#faq" class="hover:text-brand-red">→ FAQ</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem Narrative Section -->
  <section class="section bg-white" id="problem">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-6">Why Running a Dog Daycare Is Harder Than It Should Be</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">
          You opened a dog daycare because you love dogs. But somewhere between the morning drop-off rush and the end-of-day admin, the spreadsheets, the phone calls, and the WhatsApp messages took over. Sound familiar?
        </p>

        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
          Most daycare owners tell us the same thing: they spend more time on administration than they ever expected. A typical day looks like this: Calls and texts from owners asking if spots are available. Manually updating a spreadsheet that two staff members are editing at the same time. Realising at 8am that you've double-booked the large dog playgroup again. Rifling through a filing cabinet to check whether Buddy's kennel cough is still in date before he arrives. Writing out five WhatsApp updates to anxious owners who want to know how their dog is getting on.
        </p>

        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
          And that's before you factor in no-shows. A dog doesn't turn up on a Monday morning, the slot you held for them is empty, and there's no deposit to cover it. You lose the income and spend ten minutes calling to find out what happened.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-brand-red p-6 my-8 rounded">
          <p class="font-bold text-brand-navy mb-2">The Admin Tax on UK Daycare Operators</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700">Our conversations with UK dog daycare operators suggest many spend <strong>3–4 hours per day on administration</strong> that could be automated: booking calls, vaccine chasing, rescheduling, and manual reporting. At £15/hour in staff costs, that's £11,000–15,000 per year in time that isn't spent caring for dogs or growing the business.</p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
          The root cause is almost always the same: the wrong tools. Spreadsheets weren't designed for managing 30 dogs a day. Generic booking systems don't understand playgroups or vaccination expiry. Paper forms get lost. WhatsApp is not a business communication system.
        </p>

        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          The good news is that dedicated dog daycare software solves each of these problems specifically — not by adding more complexity, but by replacing manual tasks with automation that runs in the background while you get on with the actual work.
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-8">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3 bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
            <span class="text-brand-red text-2xl font-bold leading-none">✗</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-semibold text-brand-navy text-sm">Before: Spreadsheets + WhatsApp</p>
              <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">3–4 hrs/day on admin, double-bookings during holidays, vaccine chasing every morning</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3 bg-green-50 p-4 rounded-lg border border-green-200">
            <span class="text-green-600 text-2xl font-bold leading-none">✓</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-semibold text-brand-navy text-sm">After: MyPetCare</p>
              <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">45–60 min/day on admin, zero double-bookings, automated vaccine alerts</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What Is Section -->
  <section class="section bg-gray-50" id="what-is">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-6">What Dog Daycare Software Actually Does</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">
          <strong>Dog daycare software</strong> is a specialised management platform built for the specific way daycare facilities operate — which is quite different from a hotel booking system or a generic appointment scheduler. Daycare is high-frequency, multi-dog, and operationally complex: you're managing playgroup sizes, vaccination compliance, check-in times, and owner communication simultaneously, often with limited staff during a busy morning rush.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
          A purpose-built platform handles all of this from one interface. Owners book online and pay deposits without calling. The system enforces capacity rules by playgroup, weight class, or temperament before a booking is confirmed. Vaccination records are stored against each pet profile with automatic expiry alerts. Staff can check dogs in and out from a tablet at the front desk. Report cards with photos go out to owners during the day without anyone composing a WhatsApp message. At the end of the month, invoicing runs automatically.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
          At MyPetCare, we built the platform specifically for mixed-service pet care facilities — so if you also run <a href="/dog-boarding-software/" class="text-brand-red hover:underline">dog boarding</a>, a <a href="/kennel-software/" class="text-brand-red hover:underline">kennel</a>, or a <a href="/cattery-software/" class="text-brand-red hover:underline">cattery</a>, you manage everything from one login. No switching between systems, no duplicate pet profiles, no separate billing tools.
        </p>

        <figure class="screenshot">
          <img
            src="/images/screenshots/dashboard.png"
            alt="petcare.software dashboard showing today's check-ins, arrivals and boarding overview"
            width="1200"
            height="675"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption>See everything happening today at a glance — arrivals, check-ins, departures and boarding status</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Features Section -->
  <section class="section bg-white" id="features">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-4">Key Features of Dog Daycare Software</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-10">The features that matter most aren't a long checklist — they're the six things that eat your day if you're doing them manually.</p>

        <!-- Feature 1: Online Booking -->
        <div class="mb-16">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-4">1. Online Booking with Real-Time Availability</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            The single biggest time-saver for most daycare operators is moving bookings online. When owners can see real-time availability and book directly, you stop receiving calls to ask "do you have space on Thursday?" that interrupt your morning routine. Bookings made through the system are instantly reflected in your capacity — there's no window where a double-booking can slip through between one staff member's spreadsheet and another's diary.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            MyPetCare's booking flow asks owners the questions that matter: the dog's size and temperament, their regular schedule, any special notes for staff. Deposits can be collected at point of booking — a small friction that dramatically reduces no-shows without putting regular customers off. The booking widget embeds on your own website or links from your Google Business Profile.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
            Many facilities report that 60–70% of new bookings switch to online within the first month, cutting phone booking time by several hours per week. Read more: <a href="/blog/is-dog-daycare-software-worth-it/" class="text-brand-red hover:underline">Is Dog Daycare Software Worth It? An Honest Assessment</a>.
          </p>
          <figure class="screenshot">
            <img
              src="/images/screenshots/arrivals-depatures-report.png"
              alt="Arrivals and departures report with vaccination alerts and payment alerts highlighted"
              width="1200"
              height="675"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption>Arrivals &amp; Departures report flags vaccination expiries and outstanding balances before check-in</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <!-- Feature 2: Capacity & Playgroup Management -->
        <div class="mb-16">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-4">2. Capacity Management by Playgroup</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            Generic booking systems count bodies. Dog daycare is more complicated: a 30-dog facility might have a large dog group capped at 12, a small dog group capped at 15, and a reactive dog area capped at 3. A booking system that only tracks total capacity will let you inadvertently overbook the large group even when the total is under 30. The result on a busy Monday morning is a dog arriving that doesn't fit into any group.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            MyPetCare's capacity rules operate at playgroup level. You define groups by weight class, temperament, or any criteria you choose. When a group is full, the system makes those slots unavailable automatically — owners cannot book them and staff cannot accidentally assign a dog there. Holiday periods, which are historically the source of most double-bookings, are handled the same way: the system applies the same rules regardless of how busy it gets.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
            For facilities with mixed services, capacity rules extend across service types. A dog already booked for boarding cannot also appear as an available daycare slot for the same period.
          </p>
          <figure class="screenshot">
            <img
              src="/images/screenshots/vacinnation-tracker-report.png"
              alt="Vaccination tracker showing compliant, expiring soon and expired status across all pets"
              width="1200"
              height="675"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption>Vaccination tracker — filter by status and contact owners with expiring records in one click</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <!-- Feature 3: Vaccination Tracking -->
        <div class="mb-16">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-4">3. Vaccination Tracking and Compliance Alerts</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            Vaccine compliance is not optional for a licensed dog daycare — it's both a legal requirement and a basic duty of care to the other dogs in your facility. The problem with managing this manually is that the spreadsheet you updated six months ago doesn't remind you when something expires. Every morning requires a manual check, and with 30+ regular customers cycling through, something will eventually slip through.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            The vaccination tracker in MyPetCare stores each pet's vaccine certificates (owners can upload directly, or staff can scan them at check-in) with exact expiry dates. The system sends owners automatic reminder emails 30 and 60 days before vaccines lapse, giving them time to book a vet appointment without urgent chasing from you. If a certificate expires and no update is uploaded, the system flags the pet's next booking and can be configured to block new bookings until the record is current.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
            For facilities preparing for local authority licence inspections, the vaccination tracker provides a complete digital record of compliance — no filing cabinets, no printed spreadsheets, no last-minute scramble. See also: <a href="/blog/vaccination-tracking-for-kennels/" class="text-brand-red hover:underline">Vaccination Tracking for Dog Facilities: A Practical Guide</a>.
          </p>
          <figure class="screenshot">
            <img
              src="/images/screenshots/calendar-report.png"
              alt="Monthly calendar view showing room assignments and booking status across all kennels"
              width="1200"
              height="675"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption>Calendar view shows every booking, room assignment and status across the full month</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <!-- Feature 4: Report Cards -->
        <div class="mb-16">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-4">4. Digital Report Cards with Photo Sharing</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            Report cards are one of the highest-impact features for customer retention that most daycare operators underestimate. Dog owners who receive a photo update and a note about their dog's day are significantly more likely to re-book, refer friends, and leave positive reviews. It's a five-minute investment per dog that generates loyalty worth far more than the cost of the software.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            MyPetCare's report cards let staff capture photos from their phone, add a quick note about how the session went, and send it directly to the owner with one tap. The card goes out via email with your facility's branding — not a WhatsApp message from a staff member's personal phone. Owners see the report in their owner portal alongside the booking history, vaccine records, and upcoming schedule.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
            For facilities with high volumes, report cards can be sent as a batch at a set time each afternoon, or triggered individually when a dog checks out. Either way, owners receive personalised updates without staff spending 20 minutes composing messages.
          </p>
          <figure class="screenshot">
            <img
              src="/images/screenshots/sales-report.png"
              alt="Sales report showing total revenue, booking count and average booking value by service type"
              width="1200"
              height="675"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption>Sales report breaks down revenue by service type with daily averages and top customers</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <!-- Feature 5: Add-ons and Upsells -->
        <div class="mb-16">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-4">5. Add-ons and Upsell During Booking</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            Online booking creates a natural opportunity to offer additional services at the point of checkout — something that's awkward to do on a phone call but feels natural in a booking flow. Enrichment sessions, nail trims, grooming, training reinforcement, or premium daycare packages can all be presented as optional upgrades when an owner books a regular session.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            MyPetCare lets you configure any number of add-ons with their own pricing, time slots, and availability. An owner booking a full-day session might be offered a nail trim for £12 or an enrichment pack for £8. These are selected during the booking flow and paid as part of the deposit. The result is a higher average booking value without any sales effort from staff.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
            Facilities that enable add-ons typically see average booking values increase by 15–25% within the first quarter. Combined with reduced no-shows, the revenue impact is often enough to cover the software cost within the first month.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Feature 6: Automated Reminders -->
        <div class="mb-8">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-4">6. Automated Reminders and Owner Communication</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            Missed bookings and late cancellations almost always happen because the owner forgot. A reminder sent 24–48 hours before a booking gives them time to cancel and release the slot, or simply remember to show up. Without automated reminders, no-shows are a predictable weekly problem. With them, they drop to occasional exceptions.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            MyPetCare sends customisable email reminders on a schedule you set — 48 hours before, 24 hours before, or both. Reminders include the booking details, your cancellation policy, and a direct link to the owner portal to reschedule. SMS reminders are available in beta for facilities that want an additional touchpoint. Owners who receive reminders also cancel earlier, giving you more time to fill the slot from a waiting list.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
            Beyond booking reminders, the system automates vaccination expiry notices, post-visit thank-you messages, and re-booking prompts for regular customers who haven't booked in a few weeks. This level of communication takes significant time to maintain manually but runs itself once configured. Related: <a href="/blog/reduce-no-shows-pet-business/" class="text-brand-red hover:underline">How to Reduce No-Shows in Your Pet Business</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

