              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-1">Double-bookings in 6 months</p>
            </div>
            <div class="text-center">
              <p class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand-red">+19%</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-1">Revenue from add-on upsells</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-3">The Problem</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            Emma Thornton opened Tails & Trails in Clifton, Bristol with a 28-dog capacity and a solid reputation built through word-of-mouth. The facility ran a large dog group, a small dog group, and a limited reactive dog area. Emma managed everything with a Google Sheet and a WhatsApp group for the team.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
            The spreadsheet worked until it didn't. During the August bank holiday period, two staff members made bookings without checking each other's updates and overbooked the large group by three dogs. Two families arrived on the same morning to drop off dogs that couldn't both be placed. Emma spent an hour apologising, finding alternative arrangements, and refunding deposits. "The trust damage was worse than the financial cost," she said.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
            Beyond the holiday crises, everyday admin was quietly consuming hours. Checking vaccination certificates manually each morning. Responding to "do you have space?" WhatsApp messages throughout the day. Writing individual update messages to owners who called at noon to ask about their dog. Managing invoicing at month end by copying data from the spreadsheet into their accounting software.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-3">The Switch</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
            Emma joined MyPetCare's early access programme and set up the system over a weekend. Her three playgroups were configured with capacity rules. Regular customers were imported with their dogs' vaccine records. The booking widget went live on her website on the Monday morning. Within a week, over 60% of bookings were coming through online without any phone calls.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-brand-navy mb-3">The Results</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            Six months on, Emma's daily administration takes around 45 minutes instead of three hours. The online booking system fields availability requests, collects deposits, and confirms bookings without staff involvement. The vaccination tracker sends automatic renewal reminders, and Emma's compliance check at the start of each day takes a single click rather than a manual spreadsheet scan.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            There have been no double-bookings since go-live. The capacity rules handle bank holidays, half terms, and Christmas the same way as any other week — the system won't accept bookings that exceed group limits regardless of how in-demand those periods are.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700">
            Revenue increased by 19% within the first quarter, driven primarily by the nail trim and enrichment session add-ons that owners now select at booking. "I thought adding upsells would feel pushy," Emma said. "But when owners choose them during the booking flow, it's completely natural. It doesn't feel like we're selling at all."
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 italic">* This case study is based on typical outcomes reported by early access customers and composites several similar facilities. Individual results vary.</p>
      </div>
